This work is about face recognition using unsupervised learning method to reduce dimensionality of the data and then apply other models to classify data to a unique Id that each person has.

About Data¶

The data was taken from Kaggle Website, where the images are already pixelized and in grayscale. It is not necessary, but makes the work easier and faster.

Data consists in 400 face images of 64 x 64 pixels. Each person has 10 different photos. The images are already in the same size, so they do not need to be chopped or scaled. All backgrounds are black. To get accuracy, I asked for the data owner to upload the labels data frame.

After a first look at the images, the next step is to make images flatten and put them all in a data frame, where each column is a pixel and each row is an image. Get_image method does that and makes the train-test split and defines data.X and target data.Y.

In [4]:
class get_image:
    def __init__(self, dsize_x, dsize_y):
        dsize = (dsize_x, dsize_y)
        
        labels=[]
        pix_img=list()
        for image in faces_image:
            image1 = image.flatten()
            pix_img.append(image1)
            
            
        self.size = (len(pix_img), dsize_x, dsize_y )
        img_names = os.listdir('bw-pic')
        
        uniqueWord = [];
        num_lab=[]
        for elt in labels:
            if elt not in uniqueWord:
                uniqueWord.append(elt);
        
        for word in labels:
            num_lab.append(uniqueWord.index(word) + 1)
        
        
        df = pd.DataFrame(num_lab, columns = ['labels'])
        df['labels'] = labelss
        self.y= df['labels']
        self.X=pd.DataFrame(pix_img)
        self.X_train, self.X_test, self.y_train, self.y_test = train_test_split(self.X, self.y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
        
        
def show_img(data, unique_ids):
    fig, ax_arr = plt.subplots( 5 , 8, figsize = (20,10))
    ax_arr=ax_arr.flatten()
    for unique_id in unique_ids:
        idx = unique_id*10
        ax_arr[unique_id].imshow(data[idx], cmap = 'bone')
        ax_arr[unique_id].set_xticks([])
        ax_arr[unique_id].set_yticks([])
    plt.suptitle("Each distinct people in the dataset")

Even if the data provider have told us that there is 10 images from each person, it is important to check it. The pros of checking it is to reduce bias in training models and to check data integrity. In this case, all images have the same dimensions, otherwise we would have to scale it in order to do comparisions.

Dimensionality Reduction using PCA¶

First of all, we need to standardize data. In other words, extract the mean and divide it by its standard deviation. In practical meaning, we remove the mean face from each one of the images. N_components parameter must be set accordingly to the total explained variance and model execution time. Image recognition can be a lot slower when dealing with videos, as it must be fast and continuous. Other case that can requires greater speeds are when dealing with a large image database. So it usually happens that very sophisticated models works with less speed than necessary.

After applying Principal Component Analysis, the model decomposed the data in some faces, wich are called eigenfaces. Each one of peoples image can be reconstructed by adding each weighted eigenface.

PCA transformed data can be used with many classification models. The models that will be used in this work are KNN, SVM, KMeans++ and XGBoost Classfier. All methods are going to pass by a hyperparameter tunning, looking for the best parameters to fit the models. After modeling data, there will be comparition between them, where not only accuracy will be measured, but the fitting time and score time will be taken into the account too.

Models¶

PCA transformed data can be used with many classification models. The models that will be used in this work are KNN, SVM, KMeans++ and XGBoost Classfier. All methods are going to pass by a hyperparameter tunning, looking for the best parameters to fit the models. After all models construction there will be comparition between them, where not only accuracy will be measured, but the fitting time and score time will be taken into the account too.

KNN¶

Looking at the theoretical foundations, Knn seems to be an good model. The faces can be angled in the images, but the data set is well framed and with monocolor background, making possible to evaluate the faces only by distance.

Kmeans¶

Although Kmeans clustering uses distance to classify the data, it does not compare exactly pixels but cluster distances. This could lead to missclassification. So it is not expected to get as high as other models metric scores.

In [15]:

SVC¶

SVC works by mapping data points to a high-dimensional space and then finding the optimal hyperplane that divides the data into two classes.

In [16]:
param_grid = {
    "C": loguniform(1e1, 1e5),
    "gamma": loguniform(1e-4, 1e1),
    'kernel':["rbf", "linear", 'poly', 'sigmoid']
}


clf_svm = RandomizedSearchCV(

)

XGBoost¶

A complex model, wich will take longer to fit and score than the previous models. Is known as a precise method but due to its many steps, it is expected to take the longest times of all the models. There are many hyper parameters to set, so the hyper parameter tunning will be done in three steps. Each parameter will be adjusted in the following to find

I took the olivetti dataset and added 10 different photos of me to see how SVC performs. The photos are tottaly different from the original data, and no black background could lead to high miss classification. By the way it is a good experiment to see how it will work.

In [ ]:
class get_image_from_folder:
    def __init__(self, dsize_x, dsize_y):
        dsize = (dsize_x, dsize_y)
        i=0
        labels=[]
        pix_img=list()
        for image in images_path:
            img = cv2.imread(image) 
            folder=os.path.split(os.path.dirname(image))[-1]
            gray_img = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
            gray_img = cv2.resize(gray_img, dsize)
            gray_img_pix = gray_img.flatten()
            pix_img.append(gray_img_pix)
            cv2.imwrite('bw-pic/image%02i.jpg' %i, gray_img)
            labels.append(folder)
            i=i+1

        img_names = os.listdir('bw-pic')
        
        uniqueWord = [];
        num_lab=[]
        for elt in labels:
            if elt not in uniqueWord:
                uniqueWord.append(elt);
        
        for word in labels:
            num_lab.append(uniqueWord.index(word) + 1)
        
        
        df = pd.DataFrame(num_lab, columns = ['labels'])
        self.y= df['labels']
        self.X=pd.DataFrame(pix_img)
        
        self.X_train, self.X_test, self.y_train, self.y_test = train_test_split(self.X, self.y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
